# 🌆 Urban Pollution & Human Health Monitor

A modern, real-time **Air Quality Index (AQI)** web application that detects your location, fetches live pollution data from the OpenWeatherMap API, and displays color-coded health recommendations — all without any backend.

---

## ✨ Features

| Feature | Description |
|---|---|
| 📍 **Geolocation** | Auto-detect your coordinates via the browser |
| 🔍 **City Search** | Search any city worldwide for its AQI |
| 🎨 **Signal Colors** | Green / Yellow / Orange / Red / Purple indicators |
| 💊 **Health Tips** | Contextual health recommendations per AQI level |
| 📊 **History Chart** | Rolling AQI history graph (Chart.js) |
| 🗺️ **Pollution Map** | Live Leaflet map with PM2.5 tile overlay |
| 🧪 **Pollutant Breakdown** | CO, NO₂, O₃, SO₂, PM2.5, PM10, NH₃ bars |
| 📱 **Responsive** | Works on mobile, tablet, and desktop |

---

## 🗂️ Project Structure

```
project-folder/
├── index.html   ← App entry point (structure + scripts)
├── style.css    ← All styles (dark industrial theme)
├── script.js    ← API logic, chart, map, UI updates
└── README.md    ← This file
```

---

## 🚀 Running Locally (VS Code)

### Option A — Live Server Extension (recommended)

1. **Install VS Code** → [code.visualstudio.com](https://code.visualstudio.com)
2. **Open the project folder** in VS Code (`File → Open Folder`)
3. Install the **Live Server** extension by Ritwick Dey (search in Extensions panel)
4. Right-click `index.html` → **"Open with Live Server"**
5. Your browser opens at `http://127.0.0.1:5500`

> ⚠️ **Important:** Browser geolocation requires either `localhost` or HTTPS. Live Server satisfies the `localhost` requirement automatically.

### Option B — Python HTTP Server

```bash
# Navigate to the project folder
cd project-folder

# Python 3
python -m http.server 8080

# Then open http://localhost:8080 in your browser
```

### Option C — Node.js `http-server`

```bash
npm install -g http-server
cd project-folder
http-server -p 8080
# Open http://localhost:8080
```

---

## ☁️ Deploying to GitHub Pages (Free Live URL)

### Step 1 — Create a GitHub Account
Go to [github.com](https://github.com) and sign up if you haven't already.

### Step 2 — Create a New Repository

1. Click the **"+"** icon → **"New repository"**
2. Name it: `urban-pollution-monitor` (or any name)
3. Set to **Public**
4. Click **"Create repository"**

### Step 3 — Upload Your Files

**Via GitHub Web UI (easiest):**
1. In your new repo, click **"Add file" → "Upload files"**
2. Drag and drop all 4 files (`index.html`, `style.css`, `script.js`, `README.md`)
3. Click **"Commit changes"**

**Via Git CLI:**
```bash
# Inside your project folder
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit — Urban Pollution Monitor"

# Replace YOUR_USERNAME and YOUR_REPO_NAME below
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO_NAME.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
```

### Step 4 — Enable GitHub Pages

1. Go to your repo on GitHub
2. Click **"Settings"** tab
3. In the left sidebar, click **"Pages"**
4. Under **"Branch"**, select `main` and folder `/ (root)`
5. Click **"Save"**

### Step 5 — Get Your Live URL 🎉

After ~60 seconds, GitHub Pages will publish your site at:

```
https://YOUR_USERNAME.github.io/YOUR_REPO_NAME/
```

That's your permanent, shareable live link!

